#select numeric features
numerical_features = data.select_dtypes(include=["int64","float64"])
numerical_features.columns
Out[579]:
Index(['Age', 'Education', 'Usage', 'Fitness', 'Income', 'Miles'], dtype='object')

Reference note from, https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy-0.14.0/reference/generated/scipy.stats.skew.html
"For normally distributed data, the skewness should be about 0. A skewness value > 0 means that there is more weight in the left tail of the distribution."

In [580]:
#Utilize a lambda function and call to scipy skew to return skew value for the numeric features
skewed_features = numerical_features.apply(lambda x : skew(x.dropna())).sort_values(ascending=False)

#apply the test for highly skewed as > 0.7
skewness=skewed_features[abs(skewed_features)>0.7]
#print the results
print ("There are {} highly skewed numerical features.".format(skewness.shape[0]),"\n",skewness)

There are 4 highly skewed numerical features. 
 Miles     1.710092
Income    1.280995
Age       0.973957
Usage     0.733318
dtype: float64

Consistent with the visual indication above, for example, Age shows skewness along with Miles, Income and Usage¶

Correlation

  • looking at the strength of variable correlation helps surface interesting relationships
  • as a rule of thumb, correlation coefficients greater than 0.6 are interesting, whether positive or negative
  • a corr coeff of 1.0 is perfect correlation

TM798 conclusions

- Gender use is heavily dominated by males; very few females<br>
- Most customers are partnered and under 30 years of age<br>
- No customers report a fitness level below 3<br>
- Most customers are level 4 or level 5 fitness<br>
- The median age is 27 years for TM798 customers<br>
- Age and Income are positively correlated<br>

Overall, the TM798 customer base is the smallest in number of customers, and the highest fitness levels and income

Additional Conclusions

TM195

- most used product model with customers in each of the five fitness levels<br>
- largely centered around fitness level 3<br>
- customers are late 20s and partnered<br>
- customer median income levels are below 50K<br><br>

TM498

- ranks second in product usage<br>
- largely centered around fitness level 3<br>
- customers are late 20s and partnered<br>
- customer median income levels are below 70K<br><br>

TM798

- ranks third in product usage with customers in level 3 or higher fitness<br>
- largely centered around fitness level 5, significantly higher than other products<br>
- customers are late 20s and partnered ... and almost entirely male<br>
- the females in this very fit category tend to run more mileage for the same usage<br>
- customer median income levels are also highest, 77K. With a maximum income of 105K<br>

Trying different visualizations was very helpful. Forcing myself to investigate and then describe or summarize the relationships between variables often led to new questions about other relationships, and more iteration. So, I feel there are many more aspects to investigate. There are also likely much more efficient ways of coding. Very interesting!
